[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering native image tests**\n\nI'm thinking about the native image network and whether I should add everything as testRuntimeOnly with classifiers. It seems like there's a Gradle conflict that selects one version per configuration, which means I may have to create separate configurations. For the native image, I wonder if resources need to be included. I notice alternative tests don’t use actual ktfmt; they just create local JARs. But without reflection directly in tests, could stubs be an option? Maybe creating test source classes with specific names could work?\n\n**Evaluating native image resources**\n\nI’m considering how classpath resources and directories fit into the native image context. It seems like a native executable doesn't treat classes as separate files, which is puzzling. It might be better if the Provisioner returns the actual spotless-lib JAR. However, KtfmtStep's classloader will need to load glue classes that are packaged in spotless-lib itself. On top of that, it also requires com.facebook.ktfmt classes, which aren’t included in the spotless-lib. It’s a bit complicated!\n\n**Evaluating Gradle and native execution**\n\nI'm considering how a native executable can run after building in the same repository and access the Gradle cache. I think tests shouldn’t require network access. If I declare build dependencies, the necessary jars will be in the Gradle cache. I wonder if Gradle can generate a resource with `runtimeClasspath` and list ktfmt dependencies. Maybe I should explore using a `Provisioner` to return all current classpath files. However, I need to ensure any dependencies added will be included correctly during runtime.\n\n**Inspecting native image capabilities**\n\nI'm thinking about whether the native image supports URLClassLoader. It seems like it does, but only if the classes are in jar files on disk. In native test execution, I wonder if the original classpath jars are actually on the classpath since the executable is standalone. I'm not exactly sure about this. I should check the reachability metadata to see if it includes all necessary elements for the current classpath.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_08701a54876117250169f39d4afd9481a1886e9747b00710d2\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp851cg2xMLurkcs3wA9iarnH2CZpiy13NVFLPfiyfwlbzp80xlO5UmeAxAXtLAwr1MvnYzKOYAHlfR-SiN7YSqC5197JXcu7TlLxGTVN5nRC_FeL_2TNlrwPVx4qte_W--M_EVXetDlr9T21eibmAZklpr_bdYOOkLH01jSQHQiSspVMGOYcBDXcpC5fZWsJbStNB01Biavcs2qJPYlGgZGddftJT7GFny6k6Lbpo64oQFZ-S_pcFiYXvHLQNVyESbKv5Rfvr-8y-OIwVf-7THpSkRogPBFpqmWZctH1R2oZhULgD-wBddvtA8-9l7UPqrajvNoXRc3UuXYogQpliLNbAUkFE2IfbmOICbZWJqA2ZBsISHvpSwAVgtfheFeZ-HKiKyFKaQzhuNarni1ZFPXXPpx4MnRwhMncWDSLW1sVuf2y_rlxDRiniGvUGI-IdxgGSFB71cMtDbfuWyaVi2nQtWgo6Ersav6lFIXbU6XrXvg-MJtKrYisYGfl-R4Nfn1jHtGu1QLk0rvS_OAqWgW2EnKGXMP_cKI1V5AyG9n2Djla_8H6ft6ORzIIr0qqhV1ipgS9AB_DVI2trCeEHBqMMee3TGd6uUEUXVQMpvKUbNTvM11hoeMCx26ow52NNTpwiZjkm5phynJbugIud-7sccKJBUr0wZcjZ-lUH1g75VwDAgEDKqteWac7nrOaNSVJWpTfBZYKh0sh8arrSAiV6jFVuMqX-_0ag8ocbackmOtPsJzbwfTEOERJWv0c66GeHSlfJTHubytJREg5hNLlGawDA47Zm9N1kbdR8wTzwPiYgpEDYtSLsgIAYgaQY3sVa-105W_J2sZX-LXWfMcrxtRe2IdDLrzF-T5Ab0NOUJfXY_SCCMPCSnoM8x49t9kYIX4lcrKnx9eoykW5nM6zLnhmpW-2DNRBV8ZU9Wwo9BRSyd0gtvbiVXM0Q0tWcJ7Pfk0Y_nhScp-gwIS1uKoD-Yr8BTHGJLQ-K48eIZngcUWdC3wIKA6z4FZzBlgeWqSp9Nmquyrw4zGVJvtpZYuj8DwJpGLDvvYxi33HrDa_JlIC0XhfhqQJUuHklSbx8UmTwuYGrsXMym8zILFKCGpVUVxdb_-Ocf3CiygSF9GxXZ-HPZLOqLiPev13DcB6oHUhtDq3okVPfefyUflPyAYLBRKHkyOYpiuQbJpNSwyyMm0khDV2HBfJuKQAfqK1tYbNX1n8vWJyasNjCV95eKKDGDZhEqaBKImqZpnarZHgCJnowjaslmC4CC0k_-ANVdugooTvhCjRDeVeisuL7Z5g_MfPLrj0GNdglEgmoYrexmu69S9LTFzkBegvtlCyoikuWVSabhImUlRfBz_Qd3MRoM7d3WVSgky3c9I5kuU-0p2KCH0ajy0rYj2XSIMVIC_X5t6L6a8k8UHjDK1fyObAgkAt7bkSs6qHoxOMEgVJbbBEOwqBL4UZeQK0QEGu8I9eNbhPVvrDfjEISzS3qSskJC3VwQI1ptoZUIhki2f1Bcp2dGr6AVWBsVpEo05B4TQ-mMvT0a5AsVcjbCNfYpOJBY7RdK02E9p0smk27F-Gd9LXfECbeZuSxFjO3Qg897